<h3> Asking for an explanation </h3>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="explanation-request">When</a> asking for an explanation, the speaker ends the sentence with @HI{{@EM{{ndesuka}}}}.

This form is used when the speaker guesses a reason or cause for what has been heard and confirms to see if this is correct.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{transit}}@KJ{{environs}}@HI{{sanha}} @KJ{{time}}@KJ{{noma}} @KJ{{large}}@KJ{{heights}}@KJ{{valve}}
      @KJ{{use}}@HI{{imasene.}} @KJ{{large}}@KJ{{heights}}@HI{{ni}} @KJ{{dwell}}@HI{{nde}} @HI{{ita@EM{{ndesuka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Ms. Watanabe, you sometimes speak Osaka dialect. Have you lived in Osaka?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ndesuka}}}} is also used when the speaker asks for information about what has been seen or heard.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{omoshiroi}}@KT{{dezain}}@HI{{no}}@KJ{{shoes}}@HI{{desune.}}@HI{{dokode}}@KJ{{buy}}@HI{{tta@EM{{ndesuka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The design of your shoes is interesting. Where did you buy them?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ndesuka}}}} asks the listener to explain the reason or cause of what has been seen or heard.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{doushite@FG{{@KJ{{slow}}:oku}}reta@EM{{ndesuka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Why were you late?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
In informal speech, this may be abbreviated to @HI{{@EM{{no?}}}}.
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h3> Offering an explanation </h3>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="offer-explanation">When</a> the speaker wishes to offer an explanation, he ends the sentence with @HI{{@EM{{ndesu}}}}.

This form is used when the speaker has been asked for an explanation (which the listener does by using one of the forms above) and wishes
to state a reason or cause in the reply.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{doushite@FG{{@KJ{{slow}}:oku}}retandesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{@KT{{basu}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{come}}:ko}}nakatta@EM{{ndesu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: Why were you late?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: Because the bus didn't come.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ndesu}}}} is also used when the speaker wishes to add a reason or cause to what he has stated.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{@KJ{{every^morning^new^hear}}wo@KJ{{read}}mimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{iie.@KJ{{time^interval}}ganai@EM{{ndesu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: Do you read a newspaper every morning?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: No. I don't have the time.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
In informal speech, this may be abbreviated to @HI{{@EM{{no}}}}.
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h3> Introducing a topic </h3>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="intro">@HI{{@EM{{ndesuga}}}}</a> is used to introduce a topic.
It is often followed by a request, an invitation or an
expression seeking permission. However, the trailing clause can be omitted.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{day^book^word}}de@FG{{@KJ{{hand^paper}}:tegami}}wo@KJ{{write}}ita@EM{{ndesuga}},chotto@KJ{{see}}teitadakemasenka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I've written a letter in Japanese. Could you please check it for me?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h3>Stating the Result of a Reason or Logical Guess</h3>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The following pattern may be used to state a result that has arisen because of a particular reason or a guess based on logical grounds.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{he}}ha@KJ{{day^book}}ni@KJ{{detain^study}}shimasu. sorede@KJ{{day^book^word}}wo@KJ{{exertion^strong}}shiteirunodesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
